uint32() = 0..4294967295
.RS 2
8-bit, 24-bit and 32-bit integers occurring in Diameter and AVP headers.


.RE

avp() = #diameter_avp{}
.RS 2
The application-neutral representation of an AVP. Primarily intended for use by relay applications that need to handle arbitrary Diameter applications. A service implementing a specific Diameter application (for which it configures a dictionary) can manipulate values of type message() instead.

.PP
Fields have the following types.


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIcode = uint32()\fR\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIis_mandatory = boolean()\fR\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIneed_encryption = boolean()\fR\fR

.RE

vendor_id = uint32() | undefined
.RS 2
Values in the AVP header, corresponding to AVP Code, the M flag, P flags and Vendor-ID respectively. A Vendor-ID other than 
\fIundefined\fR implies a set V flag.

.RE

data = iolist()
.RS 2
The data bytes of the AVP.


.RE

name = atom()
.RS 2
The name of the AVP as defined in the dictionary file in question, or 
\fIundefined\fR if the AVP is unknown to the dictionary file in question.

.RE

value = term()
.RS 2
The decoded value of an AVP. Will be 
\fIundefined\fR on decode if the data bytes could not be decoded, the AVP is unknown, or if the decode format is \fInone\fR. The type of a decoded value is as document in diameter_dict(4).

.RE

type = atom()
.RS 2
The type of the AVP as specified in the dictionary file in question (or one it inherits). Possible types are 
\fIundefined\fR and the Diameter types: \fIOctetString\fR, \fIInteger32\fR, \fIInteger64\fR, \fIUnsigned32\fR, \fIUnsigned64\fR, \fIFloat32\fR, \fIFloat64\fR, \fIGrouped\fR, \fIEnumerated\fR, \fIAddress\fR, \fITime\fR, \fIUTF8String\fR, \fIDiameterIdentity\fR, \fIDiameterURI\fR, \fIIPFilterRule\fR and \fIQoSFilterRule\fR.

.RE


.RE

dictionary() = module()
.RS 2
The name of a generated dictionary module as generated by diameterc(1) or 
\fIdiameter_make:codec/2\fR. The interface provided by a dictionary module is an implementation detail that may change.

.RE

header() = #diameter_header{}
.RS 2
The record representation of the Diameter header. Values in a packet() returned by 
\fIdecode/2\fR are as extracted from the incoming message. Values set in an packet() passed to \fIencode/2\fR are preserved in the encoded binary(), with the exception of \fIlength\fR, \fIcmd_code\fR and \fIapplication_id\fR, all of which are determined by the dictionary() in question.
.PP
\fBNOTE: \fRIt is not necessary to set header fields explicitly in outgoing messages as diameter itself will set appropriate values. Setting inappropriate values can be useful for test purposes.


.PP
Fields have the following types.


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIversion = uint8()\fR\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIlength = uint24()\fR\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIcmd_code = uint24()\fR\fR

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fB\fIapplication_id = uint32()\fR\fR

.RE


